ologies. By broadly applying physical laws to the global supply chain, Rob Handfield and Tom Linton explore the impact of supply chain physics on global market policies, such as tariffs, factory location, pandemic response, supply base geographies, and outsourcing. Flow adheres to the laws of motion as guideposts for decision-making in network design, sourcing decisions, factory location, management and training, and a host of other key decisions. Chapters provide specific recommendations on what to do to improve supply chain movement, and includes important insights for managers along with engaging interviews with companies including Biogen, General Motors, Siemens, and Flex on their response to COVID-19. Flow is an important resource for management teams hoping to elevate the enterprise-level success of their organizations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Production & Operations Management.2bisacsh  aanalytics.  aautomation.  aautonomous supply chain.  acognitive analytics.  adigital transformation.  alogistics.  apredictive.  apurchasing.  arobotics.  asupply chain management.  asupply management.1 aHandfield, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLinton, Tom, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073922040uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753800240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487538002423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487538002/original  a978-3-11-073922-0  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles